There is no lack of people willing to stretch definitions to make
arguments.

Ensign Smith may have been a member of the US Navy, but he was
temporarily assigned to the another service (Coastal Command?).  He was
not under US Naval command. He was taking his orders from the military
of another country/government.

In Canada, this happens in modern day as well. There are large numbers
of Canadian Forces Personnel who do exchanges with other NATO
countries. There were Canadians fighting with the US Army in the
invasion of Iraq, and Canadians fighting there still, despite the fact
that the Canadian government didn't support the invasion. My
understanding is that in this situation, the exchange person is given
the option of staying with the unit they are assigned with or dropping
out of the program- the Canadian government/military did not/does not
just pull the plug on all exchanges.

In the case of an exchange prior to Pearl Harbour, surely the US
government would have considered the possibility/probability that
exchanged officers like Smith would end up in harm's way.

