The German navy was not actively pursuing U.S.
flag ships. The attack on REUBEN JAMES was IIRC
inadvertent, as REUBEN JAMES interposed herself
between U-552 and convoy HX-156.

Likewise, the earlier attack on KEARNY occurred
while KEARNY was actively defending a convoy with
depth charges.

However, this Wikipedia article

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_American_shots_fired_in_World_War_II

suggests that the first "shot" by American forces
against Germany was a depth charge attack by
USS NIBLACK on April 10, 1941, when NIBLACK
was rescuing survivors of a torpedoed Dutch
ship and detected a a lurking U-boat.

Note that no US force inflicted any casualties in
these actions.

The first German prisoners captured by the U.S.
were two crewmen of a Ju 88 which was shot down
on a recon mission over Iceland in late April 1942.
