The ship had positioned itself between an ammunition ship in the convoy
and the known position of a German U-Boat wolfpack.  She was hit forward
by a torpedo and her entire front end was blown off when a magazine
exploded.  She floated for 5 minutes before going down.  Of the crew, 44
survived, and 115 died.  Reuben James was the first US Navy ship sunk by
hostile action in World War II.

Surprisingly, outside of the concerned family and friends of the crew,
news of the sinking did not spark any strong public sentiment in the
U.S.  It was folk singer Woody Guthrie, who wrote a famous song "The
Sinking Of The Reuben James" immediately after the sinking, that kept
the incident from slipping into obscurity.

