Alternate WI: TEXAS and NEW YORK patrolled and
maneuvered in the Denmark Strait (which is "between
NF and Greenland") starting early in 1941. These
patrols were intermittent - one ship would go out,
patrol for a couple of weeks, then return to the
U.S.; the other ship would then steam out. BISMARCK
passed through Denmark Strait during one of the gaps
in this program.

Shift around the dates a bit, and there could be a
full-fledged battle! The US task group included a
destroyer squadron, I'm sure. So though BISMARCK
would outgun and almost surely defeat TEXAS or
NEW YORK, she'd get hurt herself and would have
difficulty _not_ getting sunk by the destroyers.
(BISMARCK's only escort was the cruiser PRINZ
EUGEN.)

So take it from there: US and German battleships
slugging it out: TEXAS sunk by BISMARCK's shells,
BISMARCK crippled by TEXAS and then sunk by the
destroyers.

Claims that BISMARCK opened fire first (as she
probably would, having better radar and expecting
to encounter British ships at any moment). Howls
for war against the German "pirates". Howls of
"provocation" and "plot" from isolationists
(including the Reds, BARBAROSSA being still a
month ahead). Accusations that FDR deliberately
sent TEXAS to her doom.

I think maybe the U.S. does declare war. It's
not Pearl Harbor, but it's semi-close.

The casus belli will be much weaker - TEXAS
was not in US waters, TEXAS was out there,
where trouble could happen, by US action.

OTOH, Hitler can't repudiate BISMARCK to get off
the hook, for one thing. He'll claim that TEXAS
fired first, and demand a US apology. That won't
wash.

There will be opposition in Congress, but the DoW
will go through.

One side effect: US Reds will be really noisy
about this, calling for strikes and sabotage
against the "capitalists' war". They will rush
out to take the lead in what will be for a while
a substantial anti-war movement, and get their
names in the papers as such.

This will leave them with _tons_ of egg on the
face on 6/23/41, and they have to flip-flop.
