In short, another of those oh-poor-Germans stories.

The London Naval Agreements accorded special protection to merchant
shipping, _provided that they did not carry out hostile behavior_. Note that
an attempt to avoid boarding and capture was considered _hostile behavior_,
which forfeited the merchant ship the right not to be attacked.
On October 17, 1939, that is before the Columbus scuttling, German subs were
ordered to sink all enemy merchant ships without warning, which means,
without giving them any chance of exercising their rights, above.
The order was not without justification, since the British had announced
measures and orders that gave Doenitz good reason to believe that resistance
by merchant vessels could be expected.

The outcome of the mutual decisions, orders and measures above, however,
changed de facto the status of the merchant shipping personnel into that of
servicemen of their countries' navies. I highlight "mutual", because it was
not a chain of decisions taken solely by the British; the Germans
contributed.
If the Germans were going to treat British merchant ships as British Royal
Navy warships, they were also going to treat the British merchant sailors as
British Navy personnel; then, there is no reason why the British should not
consider German merchant sailors as German Kriegsmarine personnel.

And assuming the US authorities agreed on such a classification, then it was
not only their right, but their duty, to intern a combatant's servicemen for
the duration of the war (Hague X 1907 Art. 15).

Note that the Columbus did attempt to escape and that its last act is an act
of resistance.

Of course, the Germans would have a claim to a different treatment of the
crew of that merchant ship if they had repatriated British merchant sailors
in compliance with Art. 6, Hague XI 1907. I have no evidence that they did,
but I'll gladly examine it if anybody can provide it.
