It was going to get worse.  The Joint Chiefs of Staff were concerned
that shipping resources to Japan was going to interfere with the US
military expansion, for one thing.  For another, Japan's foreign
exchange supplies were not infinite, and the Japanese economy was
not nearly as strong as Britain's.  Japan could not produce export
goods in large quantities and fight the war in China.

This means that, by Spring 1942 (Willmott's estimate), Japan would
be effectively bankrupt, and unable to pay for US oil and iron.

Historically, the Japanese were determined to do almost anything rather
than give up the war in China.  I do not believe they would have
quietly admitted failure just because they ran out of foreign
exchange.  I think they would have acted much as historically, and
would have tried to seize resource-containing areas (such as the
Dutch East Indies) to keep the war going.

There's also the fact that the last and strictest embargo was in
response to the Japanese move into southern Indochina.  That move
was not related to the war in China.  It was an independent resource
grab and the seizure of bases useful for later conquest.  It was
the start of the Japanese attacks continued in December 1941.

If we can say the Japanese were politically unable to stop the China
war, we can also say that the US was politically unable to subsidize
the China war by giving Japan whatever Japan asked for.  Therefore,
any embargo was doing no more than hastening the inevitable, and
the last embargo was a response to Japanese aggression, and not a
starting cause.

