Every right. Absolutely. And even a duty.
See Article 11 of Hague Convention V 1907, and Article 24 of Hague
Convention XIII 1907, dealing with the rights and duties of neutral powers
and persons in case of war on land and on the sea.
Troops of a belligerent that happen, in whatever way, into the territory of
a neutral, cannot leave it for the duration of the war.

An argument could be made if these men had had the right to the status of
merchant sailors. But the legal issues I raised, and that you very
significantly chose to cut away without discussing, coupled with the factual
issues raised by Mr. Clark, demonstrate that these men were rightfully
treated as servicemen of a belligerent ending up in neutral territory.
That's internment. Very fair.

Furthermore, the status of internment

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; was changed to imprisonment behind barbed wire once the US
&gt; was at war.
">

Very rightly so. Most people, by the way, would have said "once Germany
declared war on the US". At that point, they had become POWs. I'll bet that
if they had been still treated as internees, you'd be now making a fuss
about their being denied the POW status they were entitled to.
And internees under Hague 1907 had less and less defined rights than POWs
under Geneva 1929.
